    "Richard B. Vinson": "Michael Green, The `[group_Word_Luk_1]` Second Epistle of Peter `[char_Peter_Mat_4]` and the Epistle of Jude (2d ed.;\nTNTC; Grand Rapids: Wm B. Eerdmans, 1987) 140, notes that \u201csince every other refer-\nence to \u2018the fathers\u2019 in the New Testament . . . means \u2018the Old Testament fathers,\u2019 such\nI take the probable meaning here.\u201d",
    "Unknown": "The priesthood being changed (metatithemen\u00eas t\u00eas hierosun\u00eas). Genitive absolute with present passive participle of metatith\u00eami, old [v_Gal_1_6] word to transfer (Gal 1:6). A change (metathesis). Old substantive [v_Heb_7_12] from metatith\u00eami. In N.T. only in Heb. (Heb 7:12; Heb 11:5; Heb 12:27). God's choice of another kind of priesthood for his Son, left the Levitical line off to one side, forever discounted, passed by \"the order of Aaron `[char_Aaron_Exo_6]`\" (t\u00ean taxin Aar\u00f4n).\nVerse 12 Merciful (hile\u00f4s). Old Attic adjective for hilaos, common in the LXX, only here in N.T., from which hilaskomai comes (Luke 18:13). Will I remember no more (ou m\u00ea mn\u00easth\u00f4 eti). Double negative ou m\u00ea with first aorist passive subjunctive (volitive) of mimn\u00eask\u00f4, to recall.\n12. From the east, though why is not told. Swete suggests it is because Palestine is east of Patmos. The plural apo anatol\u00f4n occurs in Mat 2:1 without h\u00ealiou (sun). The seal of the living God ( sphragida theou z\u00f4ntos ). Here the signet ring, like that used by an Oriental monarch, to give validity to the official documents. The use of z\u00f4ntos with theou accents the eternal life of God (Rev 1:18; Rev 10:6; Rev 15:7) as opposed to the ephemeral pagan gods. To whom it was given ( hois edoth\u00ea autois ). For edoth\u00ea see on Rev 6:2, 4, etc. The repetition of autois in addition to hois (both dative) is a redundant Hebraism (in vernacular Koin\u201a to some extent) often in the Apocalypse (Rev 3:8). The angels are here identified with the winds as the angels of the churches with the churches (Rev 1:20). To hurt ( adik\u00easai ). First aorist active infinitive of adike\u00f4 , subject of edoth\u00ea , common use of adike\u00f4 in this sense of to hurt in the Apocalypse (Rev 2:11; Rev 6:6 already), in Luke 10:19 also. The injury is to come by letting loose the winds, not by withholding them.\nVerse 12 Note am\u00ean at the beginning and the close of the doxology. Note also separate feminine article with each of the seven attributes given God, as in Rev 4:11; Rev 5:12,\n12. Tormented ( ebasanisan ). First aorist active indicative of basaniz\u00f4 , for which see Rev 9:\nVerse 12 Saying ( legous\u00eas ). Present active predicate participle of leg\u00f4 , feminine genitive agreeing with ph\u00f4n\u00eas , though some MSS. have the accusative ph\u00f4n\u00ean legousan , either construction being proper after \u00eakousan (they heard). There is a little evidence for \u00eakousa like Rev 12:10 (24 times in the book). Cf. John `[char_John_Ref]` 5:\nVerse 12\n12. From the east, though why is not told. Swete suggests it is because Palestine is east [v_Mat_2_1] of Patmos. The plural apo anatol\u00f4n occurs in Mat 2:1 without h\u00ealiou (sun). The seal of the living God (sphragida theou z\u00f4ntos). Here the signet ring, like that used by an Oriental monarch, to give validity to the official documents. The use of z\u00f4ntos with theou [v_Rev_1_18] accents the eternal life of God (Rev 1:18; Rev 10:6; Rev 15:7) as opposed to the ephemeral pagan gods. To whom it was given (hois [v_Rev_6_2] edoth\u00ea autois). For edoth\u00ea see on Rev 6:2, 4, etc. The repetition of autois in addition to hois (both dative) is a redundant Hebraism (in [v_Rev_3_8] vernacular Koin\u201a to some extent) often in the Apocalypse (Rev 3:8). The `[object_Temple_Hag_2]` angels are here identified with the winds as the angels of the [v_Rev_1_20] churches with the churches (Rev 1:20). To hurt (adik\u00easai). First aorist active infinitive of adike\u00f4, subject of edoth\u00ea, common use of [v_Rev_2_11] adike\u00f4 in this sense of to hurt in the Apocalypse (Rev 2:11; Rev 6:6 [v_Luk_10_19] already), in Luke 10:19 also. The injury is to come by letting loose the winds, not by withholding them.\nVerse 12 Note am\u00ean at the beginning and the close of the doxology. Note also separate feminine article with each of the seven attributes given [v_Rev_4_11] God, as in Rev 4:11; Rev 5:12,\n12. Tormented (ebasanisan). First aorist active [v_Rev_9_5] indicative of basaniz\u00f4, for which see Rev 9:\nVerse 12 Saying (legous\u00eas). Present active predicate participle of leg\u00f4, feminine genitive agreeing with ph\u00f4n\u00eas, though some MSS. have the accusative ph\u00f4n\u00ean legousan, either construction being proper after \u00eakousan (they heard). There is a little evidence for \u00eakousa like Rev [v_Jhn_5_28] 12:10 (24 times in the book). Cf. John `[char_John_Ref]` 5:",
